column16:
This table presents student enrollment by gender and race/ethnicity from 2019 through 2024. It separates men and women before combining into a university total, showing both raw counts (N) and percentages (Pct).

Men (2019–2024)

Total enrollment remained relatively steady, around 5,500–5,000 students.

White men made up the largest group, declining from 61.7% (2019) to 55.5% (2024).

Hispanic/Latino men grew notably from 13.7% (2019) to 17.9% (2024).

Black or African American men decreased slightly, from 11.7% to 10.4%.

Asian men held around 5–5.5%.

Small but consistent populations existed in “Two or more races” (~2–2.6%) and “Race unknown” (~2–2.5%).

Women (2019–2024)

Enrollment dropped from 5,613 (2019) to 4,931 (2024).

White women were the largest share, declining from 59.7% (2019) to 51.7% (2024).

Hispanic/Latina women grew significantly, from 16.8% (2019) to 22.2% (2024).

Black or African American women also saw a small increase: 11.9% ? 12.1%.

Asian women fluctuated but stayed around 4–5%.

Other categories (multiracial, race unknown) remained small but steady.

Total (2019–2024)

University-wide totals declined from 11,154 students in 2019 to 9,997 in 2024.

White students dropped from 60.6% to 53.6%, showing a steady decrease.

Hispanic/Latino students rose from 15.2% to 20.0%, now the second-largest group.

Black or African American students stayed steady around 12–12.6%.

Asian students remained ~4–5%.

Other groups (Native Hawaiian, multiracial, unknown) each represented 2–3% or less consistently.
